body:
With https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/1202 , you need to enable it by building from source. It just writes the shape info to stdout so it should work from python as well.
e.g. in Linux env, build python wheel using build.sh (build.bat in Windows)
./build.sh --config Release --cmake_extra_defines onnxruntime_DEBUG_NODE_INPUTS_OUTPUTS=ON --build_wheel --update --build

Is this build option tested?
I get this error:

 
```text
/home/ehazar/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/framework/utils.cc: In instantiation of ‘void onnxruntime::utils::DumpTensor(const onnxruntime::Tensor&, const onnxruntime::TensorShape&) [with T = int]’:
/home/ehazar/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/framework/utils.cc:638:13:   required from here
/home/ehazar/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/framework/utils.cc:566:25: error: comparison between signed and unsigned integer expressions [-Werror=sign-compare]
   for (int row = 0; row < num_rows; ++row) {
```

After it is fixed (by changing to size_t) I get 

```text
/home/ehazar/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/framework/utils.cc:560:36: error: expected primary-expression before ‘)’ token
     if (std::is_floating_point_v<T>)
```

I also removed that special case for float print, and build succeeded

issue.title: Option to dump only every node shape info

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

body:
It's a rarely used feature which is tested on Windows and currently builds without error. It adds a huge amount of overhead so most likely will never be tested via a CI build. 

What environment are you building in? std::is_floating_point_v is somewhat new and we recently downgraded to C++11 which may not have that feature. I can update the code to use std::is_floating_point<T>::value instead if that helps.
